You can use the flags tab in the save editor to check which skulltulas have been collected and how the values change based on that. (I wonder how the data is read though)

It is an array of six ints. Does each int at least correspond to a collection of areas? (Yes?)

The secret is to convert each number to 32-bit signed 2's compliment binary. (ints take up 4 bytes or 32 bits so this makes sense) Each skulltula corresponds to an index at one of these 6 numbers in binary. It starts from right to left. 
For example
Deku tree + Dodongo's Cavern = 7951 or 0001111100001111 (as a short (signed 16 bits (2 bytes)))
They might actually be stored in the order that they appear in the flag editor.
22 bytes. 

The reasoning for the seemingly arbitrary zeroes in between is because the skulltulas for each area are stored as a whole byte. Which means that each of the main areas can only have a maximum of 8 gold skulltulas. The areas are divided up into the 8 main dungeons, 2 mini dungeons, and the 12 main map areas.
Hence the 22 bytes. Because they have to be stored as ints and ints can only store 4 bytes of data, it has to be split up into 6. This at least means I have a concrete way of tracking by area, which leaves the grueling labour of having to track each one individually, but I'll get there. I've already come so far with just this.

How it is structured:
This here is int 0 from file1:
00011111 00001111 00011111 00001111
 byte 3   byte 2   byte 1   byte 0

